When assigning `self.data = initial_data`, you just create another new name for the object `initial_data`. 

The behavior you didn&#39;t expect here is caused by the fact that the default argument `initial_data` gets evaluated only once when the method gets declared, not everytime you call it, so all your instances that use it actually use the same `initial_data` dict object, that you can access under different names like `instance_a.data`, `instance_b.data` and so on.

The classic solution is to use `None` as default, like this:

    class MyClass:
        def __init__(self, initial_data=None):
            if initial_data is None:
                initial_data = {}
            self.data = initial_data

